An Introduction to Working With Open Street Maps Data¶

If you haven't read about TruFactor Routes yet, check out our intro post on Routes and what they are used for. At the end of that post we noted that a lot of work happens to verify the accuracy of TruFactor Routes. To get there, we first need to work with OSM data as it is the common layer we will match TruFactor Routes and public traffic counts against. So this tutorial will show you how to get up and running with OSM data. Open Street Maps (OSM) is a crowd sourced map of the world. The project contains both a map tile layer and a data layer. The map tile layer allows for the rendering of vector tiles in the browser (maps!). This tutorial will use OSM's tile layer to render a map in the browser. The data layer contains elements such as roads, buildings boundaries and points of interest. The underlying data layer is particularly useful for geographic analysis and is leveraged in TruFactor's Routes offering. There are not many resources showing how to extract and work with OSM data using big data tools. In this tutorial, we will demonstrate how to work with OSM data files. While one could work with the underlying .pbf file extracts, TruFactor leverages the world extract hosted on Amazon Web Services Registry for Open Data. In particular, we will leverage the .orc formatted extract which plays nice with Apache Spark. You can get the file [here](https://registry.opendata.aws/osm/). For this tutorial, we will focus on the road elements of OSM for routing purposes in North America. If you would like to learn more about OSM see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenStreetMap and https://www.openstreetmap.org/about.

Step 1: Download the latest OSM file¶

Working with OSM world file requires a bit of compute. The entire world plain xml file is over 1TB in size. The .orc file comes in at under 65GB. It is a single file which is a little unfortunate since Spark's parallel processing isn't fully leveraged until this file has been partitioned to smaller chunks.

To do so you can either:

  • transfer to local either in terminal or in notebook using magic bash command
    • you can try to use s3-dist-cp, but it reduces to a single cpu anyways since it is a single file
    • use aws cli to copy the file locally
      • then use hdfs cli to copy the file to your clusters HDFS
  • read directly from s3 using spark.read.orc()
    • we've found it to be faster to copy to local hdfs and then read

Once you have it locally, repartition the file and write out in parquet format. If you aren't familiar with parquet get some education over here. Once this step is complete, Spark's parallelism will be leveraged to its full advantage.

In [1]:
%%bash
aws s3 cp s3://osm-pds/planet/planet-latest.orc /mnt/osm
hdfs dfs -put /mnt/osm hdfs:///osm

Step 2: Filter to roads in North America¶

Intro¶

Now that the data is loaded, let's do some plotting so we can see what this data actually represents. OSM's data structure has several foundational components. The table above shows nodes and ways. Nodes are points in space while ways are lines or polygons. A collection of nodes often relate to a way. Below is a static image from https://overpass-turbo.eu/ which is exceptionally useful. However if you'd like to plot in Jupyter, you can leverage Folium to do so. Folium uses OSM vector tiles by default.


Ways and nodes might have metadata associated in the form of tags. These tags are useful for filtering to certain types of ways or nodes. Note that tags can be robust or relatively sparse. However, most ways which are navigable have tags which identify them as such.



A word of caution: Nodes and ways have versioning, and get updated by users periodically. So don't assume that data is static! If you leverage an application that uses OSM data as an input, you'll want to make sure you are leveraging the same version of data. For instance, TruFactor Routes uses Open Source Routing Machine (OSRM) to route device telemetry. When doing so, we fix the version of OSM data OSRM uses and that we use subsequently for analysis. Otherwise you may have nodes which don't align between datasets.


Filter OSM data to North America nodes and ways which are visible¶

Now we will extract the ways and their corresponding nodes. Note: only nodes have coordinates, so we have to take the nodes associated with a way to get the coordinates. Since OSM has a lot of different types of ways, we filter to highway and route keys from OSM. These are the ways for cars and foot traffic. You can find information on the highway key here: https://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Key:highway A full list of keys can be found here: https://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Category:Keys

In [10]:
#rough filter for North America nodes
nodes_NA = (osm.filter((col('type') == 'node') & 
                       (col('visible')==True) & 
                       (
                       (col('lat').between(18.421276, 49.397557) & col('lon').between(-160.633296, -65.321077)) |
                       (col('lat').between(53.168095, 71.974158) & col('lon').between(-170.422840, -126.782058))
                       )
                      )
                .select(col('id').alias('node'), 
                        col('lat').cast('double').alias('lat'), 
                        col('lon').cast('double').alias('lon'))
           )
In [11]:
raw_ways = osm.filter(col("type")=='way').withColumnRenamed('id', 'way_id')

ways1 = raw_ways.select('way_id', fns.posexplode(osm.nds).alias('pos', 'nodes'))

ways2 = ways1.join(nodes_NA, ways1.nodes.ref == nodes_NA.node)

ways3 = (ways2.select('way_id',
                     fns.struct('pos', 
                                'lat', 
                                'lon', 
                                col('node').alias('node_id')
                               ).alias('node_info')
                     )
             .groupBy('way_id')
             .agg(fns.sort_array(fns.collect_list('node_info')
                                ).alias('nodes')
                 )
        )

all_ways = raw_ways.join(ways3, 'way_id').drop(fns.col('nds'))
In [13]:
road_ways = all_ways.filter(
                        fns.array_contains(fns.map_keys(all_ways.tags), 'highway') | 
                        fns.array_contains(fns.map_keys(all_ways.tags), 'route')
                            )
In [14]:
road_ways.write.parquet('osm_ways', mode='overwrite')

Step 3: Visualize ways and nodes¶

Visualize Kansas City ways¶

Now that we've reduced OSM to North America ways and nodes which are traveled by vehicles and pedestrians let's visualize the data.

In [3]:
road_ways = spark.read.parquet('osm_ways').repartition(10000)
In [4]:
road_ways_coords = (road_ways.select('way_id', 
                                    fns.explode('nodes').alias('node')
                                    )
                            .groupBy('way_id')
                            .agg(fns.collect_list(
                                        fns.array('node.lon', 'node.lat')
                                        ).alias('way_coords')
                                )
                   )
In [5]:
kansas_city_bounds = {'lat': [39.100771, 39.108642], 'lon':[-94.587623, -94.570705]}

kansas_city_way_ids = (road_ways.select('way_id', 
                                       fns.explode('nodes').alias('node')
                                      )
                           .filter(col('node.lat').between(kansas_city_bounds['lat'][0], kansas_city_bounds['lat'][1]) & 
                                   col('node.lon').between(kansas_city_bounds['lon'][0], kansas_city_bounds['lon'][1])
                              )
                           .select('way_id').distinct()
                      )

kansas_city_ways = road_ways_coords.join(kansas_city_way_ids, 'way_id').collect()
In [6]:
import folium
osm = folium.Map(location=(39.105087, -94.577478), zoom_start=15)

for way in kansas_city_ways:
    way_geojson = {'type':'Feature','geometry':{'coordinates':way.way_coords,'type':'LineString'}}
    fol_geojson = folium.GeoJson(way_geojson)#, style_function=lambda x: {'color':'blue'})
    popup = folium.Popup('way id: ' + str(way.way_id))
    popup.add_to(fol_geojson)
    fol_geojson.add_to(osm)

In Conclusion¶

We've successfully extracted nodes and ways for North America that are generally navigable by vehicles and pedestrians. Pairing TruFactor's Routes intelligence set with OSM opens up a wide array of options. But first we'd like to gather some data which can be used to benchmark TruFactor Routes. In the next tutorial, we will show you how to take OSM data and match it to other publically available datasets which measure traffic counts. Traffic counts are used in many industries today such as transportation and urban planning, out-of-home advertising, commercial real estate and more.
